[start section id="20102"]

Newly-diagnosed stage III colon cancer.

[end section id="20102"]

[start section id="20103"]

Mr. Duran is a 55-year-old man who lives about 45 minutes away with the following oncologic history:
1. Late December screening colonoscopy showed a right-sided polyp of about 5-cm.
2. February 5 he underwent a complex colonoscopy to the cecum after which a polypectomy was done revealing a grade 2 out of 4 adenocarcinoma, T2, with less than 1-mm margins.
3. February 24 underwent right hemicolectomy (Dr. Eckel) revealing no primary tumor.  However, 1 out of 29 lymph nodes showed adenocarcinoma of 3-mm size with extranodal extension.
Patient comes here now for advice on further management.  He has no specific complaints.  Denies diarrhea, fevers, cough, abdominal pain.  Has a good appetite and good energy, though in the last three days he has noted some left lower back discomfort with some tenderness which has improved.

[end section id="20103"]

